Article Text:
NIA raids Hazaribag home of suspected ISIS operative Shahnawaz Alam;

:

HAZARIBAGThe National Investigation Agency (NIA) on Thursday carried out an early morning raid in Hazaribag in connection with the recent bomb blast near Red Fort in Delhi.A six-member NIA team, accompanied by CRPF and police personnel, reached Ansar Nagar under the jurisdiction of Pelawal police station around 5 am and searched the residence of a suspected ISIS operative, Shahnawaz Alam. Currently, Alam is in jail in Pune.The NIA and ATS teams arrived in three vehicles and immediately cordoned off the area. Over 25 CRPF personnel, including male and female commandos, secured the premises as the officers questioned family members and examined various parts of the house. An additional police force was also deployed in the neighbourhood as a precaution.Sources said the raid was based on fresh intelligence inputs regarding Alam’s suspected networks. The search lasted over 10 hours and involved scanning documents, electronic devices and material linked to extremist activities. NIA officials kept their distance from the media and local police during and after the raid. The team brought a printer into the house, prompting speculations that copies of important documents were made on the spot.Alam, originally from Hazaribag, studied at AIIMS and previously worked at diagnostic centres in Ranchi and Hazaribag.He was first arrested by Delhi Police’s special cell in 2023 for suspected ISIS connections and by the NIA in October 2023 from Pune for alleged links to an ISIS module. This was the second NIA raid at his house since that arrest.Investigations have revealed Alam’s involvement in cases of robbery and theft in Hazaribag in 2019. He spent eight to nine months in jail before securing bail in December 2020, during which he allegedly came into contact with ISIS handlers. His arrest was linked to a Pune ISIS module, where he was believed to have played a key role. Officials suspected that parts of his network remain active in Jharkhand, and he is thought to have been trained in forested areas near Pune and to have been in touch with notorious ISIS operatives.The NIA is now focusing on identifying Alam’s local connections, possible associates and materials used in terror-related activities. Officials said more revelations were expected as the investigation progressed. Sources added that many electronic gadgets were seized, though this has not been officially confirmed. Neither NIA officials nor police have shared details of the raid.Shahnawaz’s passport was issued in Ranchi on October 31, 2016 and is valid until October 30, 2026. His date of birth is recorded as March 5, 1993.
